  "texts": [
    "Historically, a major obstacle to the adoption of additive synthesis was simply the computational cost of evaluating potentially hundreds of sinusoidal components at every time step.",
    "A practical solution was to pre-compute the values of a sinusoid at a finite number of time-steps and store them in a memory buffer.",
    "This buffer can then be read periodically at varying \"frequencies\" by fractionally incrementing a circular read pointer and applying interpolation.",
    "The buffer, referred to as a wavetable, need not contain only samples from a sinusoidal function, however.",
    "Instead, it can contain any values, allowing for the specification of arbitrary harmonic spectra (excluding the effect of interpolation error) when the wavetable is read periodically."
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}